\begin_layout Section
Hedging using Futures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When one needs to purchase (sell) an asset in the future and believes the
 price will increase (decrease), a long (short) future hedge is approprite
 in order to lock the price and neutralize the risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pros of hedging:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Focus on business, minimize risks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Creates value, ensures cash
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stability (less volatility)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cons:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shareholders can diversify themselves and hedge if needed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May tie up collateral funds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Losses are difficult to explain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

perfect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 hedging often, if there is uncertainty or no contracts availability on
 the needed asset (cross-hedge) / date (choose later contract or roll forward
 rate).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
basis
\series default
 is defined as the difference between the spot price and the future price.
 
\series bold
Basis risk
\series default
 is the uncertainty about the basis when closing the hedge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hedge ration
\series default
 is the ration between the size of futures position and the size of exposure.
 The optimal ratio should be chosen to 
\series bold
minimize the variance of the total proceeds
\series default
 (somewhat similar to the CAPM model).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a future contract, the profit is always the closing price minus the opening
 price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An improperly done hedge can turn very bad, as was the case with Metallgesellsch
aft.
 They have engaged in very long-term contracts for oil supply for a locked
 price (of $21 per barrel).
 Retailers were averse to fluctuatinos in oil price and therefore willing
 to buy these contracts.
 The company believed they could purchase the oil at a low price, seeing
 an arbitrage opportunity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They ended up having exposure to 150 million barrels of oil, which was hedged
 in the futures market.
 Each month the exposure was rolled to the next one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total long position in the futures matched the short position for supply.
 Variation in the short position was not compensated in the long position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the spot market they were supplying oil at a gradually decreasing price,
 thus their supply contract have been increasing in profit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the futures curve was in 
\series bold
contango
\series default
 (which is always bad for those who are long on futures), they constantly
 bought high and sold low, leading to loss on their future stack.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stock Index Futures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Stock index futures
\series default
 allow investors to participate in the market, without actually buying or
 selling stock.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The position in synthetic, the settlement is always in cash.
 Speculators are major players in this market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a very easy and quick way to hedge a portfolio, therefore it can be
 useful for hedging a well-diversified portfolio as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, consider having a bullish position and being worried about
 a potential decline in future prices.
 One can hedge by shorting a future position in the index.
 The appropriate number of contracts is chosen according to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 of the portfolio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is to have a position in the futures market, which would offest
 the anticipapted losses.
\end_layout

