\begin_layout Section
Pricing of Forwards and Futures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up until now, future prices were taken as given.
 We will now consider their pricing and its relation to the underlying assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arbitrage opportunities involve trying to take a position in the spot market
 and an offsetting position in the futures market, such that either a zero
 investment today results in a positive CF in the future, or a positive
 CF today and zero CF in the futre.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example: spot rate is $40, 3 months forwards price is $43, interest
 rate is 5%.
 The forward price is relatively high.
 In such case, we will take the short position in the expensive one (forward)
 market and simultaneously purchase the stock in the spot market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Borrowing $40 to buy the asset and selling in the future results in a profit
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\$43-\$40.5=\$2.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the forward price is $39, the correct strategy would be to short-sell
 the stock, invest the money and enter a forward contract to buy the stock
 at $39.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Forward Price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The forward price that would prevent arbitrage opportunity would be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{0}^{T}=S_{0}\cdot(1+r)^{T}
\]

\end_inset

otherwise investors will rush to exploit it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the stock pays out a dividend before the forward maturity, its cash flows
 need to be incorporated in the price:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{t}=[S-PV(Div)]\cdot(1+r)^{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying asset is not the stock, but the stock after the dividends
 were paid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In case the dividend yield is (e.g in a stock index), the price becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{t}=S\cdot(1+r-d)^{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In case of bond, the calculation is the same (involving coupons).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prices of future contracts with different maturities are clearly highly
 correlated, as they are derived form the same underlying asset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Commodities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Commodities are priced in a similar manner - they derive from the spot price
 of the underlyihng asset.
 The difference is that there is a 
\series bold
storage cost
\series default
 which is an outcome:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{0}^{T}=(S_{0}+U)(1+r)^{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{0}^{T}=S_{0}(1+r+u)^{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that there is a possibility for a forward price to be lower than the
 theoretical price.
 The reason is related to arbitrage opportunities.
 For consumption commodities, those holding the asset may not be willing
 to sell it therefore the arbitrage cannot be performed.
 It might happen when there is a shortage in the market (e,g after there
 is a hurricane, a shortage of oil, etc).
 In such case there will be a spike in the sport price, while the forwarsd
 price will be lower.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Cost of Carry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
cost of carry
\series default
 is the cost of storage plus the interest costs, less the earned income.
\end_layout

